Tutorial Part 1: Penguins!

In this part, we will have some fun with the Palmer Penguins dataset, and we will shoehorn in a statistical learning outcome: understanding Simpsons Paradox. We will start with a simple example and gradually add features to create the final plot. By the end of this tutorial, you will be able to create a visually appealing plot with custom colours, labels, and a linear regression line.

If you want to meet the penguins properly take a look at the Palmer Penguins page.

Required Packages

You need to have the following R packages installed:

  1. ggplot2: for creating the plots (part of tidyverse - more later)
  2. palmerpenguins: for the penguin dataset

You can install them using the following commands:

install.packages("ggplot2")
install.packages("palmerpenguins")

Now, lets start by loading the required packages:

library(ggplot2)
library(palmerpenguins)

Step 1: Basic Data Inspection

The palmerpenguins library contains the dataset we need so we can just ask it to load with this command:

data(penguins)

Now lets look at the data by writing its name:

In the class I will show you a few other ways to look at the data. Notice the presence of missing data (NA) and the labelling of columns with headers and metadata (specification of type of data present, e.g., fct which means factor).

Step 2: Making Basic Plots

First lets try a simple univariate plot of the penguins weight using ggplot2:

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = body_mass_g)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_bin()`).

This is the typical form of all ggplot2 plots. The first function ggplot() is used to identify the data (data = penguins) and the aesthetic mapping (inside the aes() function), then we have a + follow by the geom that is the geometric construction that will be used to represent variation in the (aesthetically) mapped variable: here, a histogram. There is much more you can control here, but we will focus on bivariate plots in this tutorial. The warnings relate to the difficulty of plotting NA since this is not a finite value. NAs cause warnings and this is good - you should be thinking about them.

So lets try another plot. This time lets see how body mass (on the ordinate) is affected by penguin species (on the abscissa):

ggplot(data = penguins, aes(x = species, y = body_mass_g)) +
  geom_boxplot()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_boxplot()`).

Here ggplot has taken care of all the organisation and has calculated quartiles, outliers, etc. Notice that we were able to add the geom_boxplot() function on a new line. This wouldnt usually work in R because each time you press enter you are entering a new command, but it works here because the previous line ended with a +.

If you want confidence intervals on your box plots you can add the argument notch = TRUE inside the brackets of geom_boxplot(). If you prefer kernel density estimation, try geom_violin() instead of geom_boxplot(). Loads of options!

Step 3: The Classic Bivariate Approach: Scatter Plot

Now, lets create a basic scatter plot of penguin bill dimensions:

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm)) +
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

Here, we added geom_point() to create a scatter plot, and because Im lazy I just wrote penguins rather than data = penguins in the ggplot() function because the function expects that the first argument will be the data. You should be feeling a little more comfortable now. These plots all look similar. You are beginning to learn the grammar of graphics after which ggplot2 is named.

Step 4: Add Custom colours

Now, lets add custom colours to the points in our scatter plot. We will add colour = species to the aesthetic mapping to differentiate points by species.

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm, colour = species)) +
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

Now we will manually set the colours using scale_colour_manual() to assign darkorange, purple, and cyan4 to the three species:

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm, colour = species)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("darkorange", "purple", "cyan4"))
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

There are also automatic palettes available. Check using ?scale_colour_discrete for example.

Step 5: Add Labels

Next, lets add a title, subtitle, and axis labels to our plot using the labs() function:

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour = species, shape = species)) +
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("darkorange", "purple", "cyan4")) +
  labs(title = "Penguin bill dimensions",
       subtitle = "Palmer Station LTER",
       x = "Bill length (mm)",
       y = "Bill depth (mm)")
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

We used labs() to add a title, subtitle, and axis labels to the plot. Notice that we have added a title and subtitle to the plot (not usually required) and we have altered the axis labels (by explicitly declaring them). Of course, you should be careful you get this manual step right and dont label them as something they are not! R will do whatever you tell it to do, no matter how silly!

Notice that we also moved the colour = species argument into the geom_point() function inside an aes() function. The use of aes() as a wrapper means that the colour is calculated automatically, by species, exactly as in step 4. This is what aesthetic mapping is all about.

Can you see what the shape = species argument did? (Depending on the plot type, other aesthetic mappings are available such as fill).

Step 6: Add Trendline

Now lets try a simplified version with a linear trend line:

ggplot(penguins, aes(x = bill_length_mm, y = bill_depth_mm)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = TRUE, colour = "grey50") +
  labs(x = "Bill length (mm)", y = "Bill depth (mm)")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_smooth()`).
## Warning: Removed 2 rows containing missing values (`geom_point()`).

Now you see a linear regression trend line added to the plot. This suggests that as the bill length increases, the bill depth decreases. The method = "lm" argument tells it to use a linear model (try loess if you want serious smoothing). As R told us this assesses how y is influenced by x (this is shown in R model notation as y ~ x). The se = TRUE argument tells it to draw confidence intervals around the regression line. Notice that the colour of the line (grey50) is not specified inside an aes() function and therefore it is uniform and as specified.

Step 5: Down to You

Your task now is to modify the code in step 4 in order to make a separate trend line for each species.

What does this lead you to conclude about the association between bill length and bill depth?

You may find the Wikipedia page on Simpsons Paradox useful.
